            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Reyes-Ishikawa is a living embodiment of the cultural fusion that defines modern California. He was born in Oakland to a Mexican father, a classically trained chef who had immigrated to cook in the Bay Area, and a third-generation Japanese-American mother, an ikebana artist whose family had deep roots in California's Central Valley. His childhood home was a vibrant sensory landscape, filled with the scents of simmering adobo and dashi broth, and the quiet discipline of his mother\u2019s art contrasting with his father\u2019s boisterous kitchen passion.\n\nThis upbringing naturally guided him toward a Bachelor's in Hospitality Management. After graduating, Marco eschewed the corporate hotel route, diving headfirst into San Francisco's demanding restaurant scene. He spent fifteen years learning the trade from the ground up: bartending in North Beach, managing a chaotic kitchen in the Mission, and observing the razor-thin margins of fine dining. The 2008 financial crisis was his crucible, teaching him fiscal discipline as he watched established restaurants shutter overnight.\n\nHis turning point came at age 38. With savings and a loan, he opened \"Puente\" (The Bridge), a restaurant and bar in Hayes Valley. The concept was his life story on a plate: Japanese precision applied to Mexican flavors, featuring dishes like carnitas gyoza and uni tostadas. The bar specialized in tequila and Japanese whisky. The pandemic nearly broke him, but his pivot to elaborate take-out kits and a beloved parklet saved the business, cementing his status as a neighborhood anchor.\n\nToday, Marco\u2019s life is his work. He lives in a condo just a 0.7-mile walk from Puente. His daily routine involves a morning espresso at a local caf\u00e9, followed by paperwork, and then the walk to his restaurant for the afternoon prep and evening service. His partner of twelve years, David, a software engineer, provides a calm counterpoint to his chaotic industry. Marco\u2019s dream is not expansion, but legacy. He hopes to mentor a young chef to eventually take over, ensuring Puente remains a cherished San Francisco institution long after he has retired. He sees his success not in his income, but in the familiar faces of regulars who fill his bar, creating a community in the heart of the city he calls home."
